[1] Summary

A broken access control vulnerability was identified in a logging-related feature of the application.

The issue arises from the use of a client-controlled user identifier parameter that is processed without verifying its association with the authenticated session.

As a result, authenticated users can impersonate other users in logging operations and manipulate access log data, compromising the integrity and reliability of audit mechanisms.

⸻

[2] Vulnerability Classification
	•	Category: Broken Access Control
	•	OWASP Top 10: A01:2021 – Broken Access Control
	•	Attack Vector: Authenticated user (low privilege)
	•	Required Privileges: Standard user account

⸻

[3] Technical Details

During testing with a standard user account, it was observed that a logging-related endpoint accepted a user identifier parameter directly from client requests.

This parameter was used in sensitive operations without verifying whether the authenticated user was authorized to act on behalf of the specified identifier.

By modifying this parameter using browser developer tools, it was possible to:
	•	Impersonate arbitrary users in logging-related actions
	•	Inject or manipulate access log records
	•	Perform operations beyond the intended privilege level

This behavior indicates a lack of binding between the authenticated session and the user identifier used in the request.

⸻

[4] Steps to Reproduce
	1.	Log in using a standard user account
	2.	Access the logging-related feature
	3.	Intercept or modify the outgoing request using browser developer tools
	4.	Identify and alter the user identifier parameter
	5.	Submit the modified request
	6.	Observe that the operation succeeds without proper authorization validation

⸻

[5] Impact Assessment

Integrity – High
Unauthorized manipulation of user identifiers and access logs directly compromises system data integrity and audit reliability.

Confidentiality – Medium to High
Improper validation may allow indirect access to or manipulation of sensitive information.

Availability – Medium
Potential abuse of the vulnerability could degrade trust in logging systems and impact operational reliability.

⸻

[6] Root Cause
	•	Lack of server-side authorization checks on sensitive operations
	•	Absence of binding between authenticated session and user identifier
	•	Use of client-controlled input in security-critical logic

⸻

[7] Remediation Recommendations
	1.	Enforce strict server-side authorization checks for all sensitive operations
	2.	Bind user identity strictly to the authenticated session context
	3.	Avoid using client-supplied identifiers in security-critical decisions
	4.	Restrict access to internal or administrative functionality
	5.	Implement centralized authorization logic and validation mechanisms

